04426nam a22006015i 9780822395959DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20142014ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223959597 a10.1515/97808223959592doi  a(DE-B1597)553877  a(OCoLC)868026323  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aN72.P6bF45 2014eb 7aART0151102bisacsh04a709.44/09045223  aLM 101972rvk0(DE-625)rvk/101012:1 aFeldman, Hannah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom a Nation Torn :bDecolonizing Art and Representation in France, 1945-1962 /cHannah Feldman. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b84 illustrations (inclu. 21 in color)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArt History Publication Initiative00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION: Art during War and the Potentialities of Decolonial Representation -- tI. FRAGMENTS AND FAÇADES: ANDRÉ MALRAUX AND THE IMAGE OF THE PAST AS THE FUTURE OF THE PRESENT -- t1. Fragments; or, The Ends of Photography -- t2. Façades; or, The Space of Silence -- tII. BETWEEN RESISTANCE AND REFUSAL: THE LANGUAGE OF ART AND ITS PUBLICS -- t3. Sonic Youth, Sonic Space: Isidore Isou and the Lettrist Acoustics of Deterritorialization -- t4. La France Déchirée: The Politics of Representation and the Spaces In-Between -- tIII. REIDENTIFICATIONS: SEEING CITIZENS BEING SEEN -- t5. "The Eye of History": Photojournalism, Protest, and the Manifestation of 17 October 1961 -- t6. Looking Past the State of Emergency: A Coda -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom a Nation Torn provides a powerful critique of art history's understanding of French modernism and the historical circumstances that shaped its production and reception. Within art history, the aesthetic practices and theories that emerged in France from the late 1940s into the 1960s are demarcated as postwar. Yet it was during these very decades that France fought a protracted series of wars to maintain its far-flung colonial empire. Given that French modernism was created during, rather than after, war, Hannah Feldman argues that its interpretation must incorporate the tumultuous "decades of decolonization"and their profound influence on visual and public culture. Focusing on the Algerian War of Independence (1954-1962) and the historical continuities it presented with the experience of the Second World War, Feldman highlights decolonization's formative effects on art and related theories of representation, both political and aesthetic. Ultimately, From a Nation Torn constitutes a profound exploration of how certain populations and events are rendered invisible and their omission naturalized within histories of modernity.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aArt and statezFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aDecolonizationxSocial aspectszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 4aFrench modernism. 4aIsidore Isou. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395959zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395959423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395959.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles